# Promise Chaining

One of the best features of promises is the ability to chain operations. Each `.then()` returns a new promise, allowing you to sequence asynchronous tasks.

```javascript
fs.readFile('file1.txt', 'utf8')
  .then(data1 => {
    console.log('File1 done');
    return fs.readFile('file2.txt', 'utf8');
  })
  .then(data2 => {
    console.log('File2 done');
    return fs.writeFile('combined.txt', data1 + data2);
  })
  .then(() => {
    console.log('All done');
  })
  .catch(err => {
    console.error('Error:', err);
  });
```

Note: `data1` is accessible only in the first `.then()`. To use it later, you could nest or use `Promise.all` (covered later).

## Error Handling

If any promise in the chain rejects, the control jumps to the nearest `.catch()` down the chain. This is similar to `try/catch` in synchronous code.

```javascript
doSomething()
  .then(result => doSomethingElse(result))
  .then(newResult => doThird(newResult))
  .catch(err => {
    // Handles errors from any of the above
    console.error('Something went wrong:', err);
  });
```

You can also have multiple `.catch()` for different stages, but usually one at the end suffices.

